  @doc """
  Defines system safety constraints for container operations.
  
  ## Agent Notes
  Safety constraints are non-negotiable requirements that must be maintained
  throughout all container operations. Violations indicate system safety issues.
  """
  def define_safety_constraints do
    IO.puts """
    📋 STEP 1: SAFETY CONSTRAINTS DEFINITION
    ======================================
    
    ## System Safety Constraints for Container Operations
    
    ### SC-1: Container Isolation Safety
    **Constraint**: Container operations must not compromise host system security
    **Rationale**: Prevent container escape or privilege escalation
    **Scope**: All container creation, execution, and termination operations
    
    ### SC-2: Data Integrity Safety  
    **Constraint**: Development data must not be corrupted or lost during container operations
    **Rationale**: Preserve work products and prevent data loss incidents
    **Scope**: Volume mounts, file operations, database interactions
    
    ### SC-3: Resource Management Safety
    **Constraint**: Container resource usage must not cause system unavailability
    **Rationale**: Prevent resource exhaustion affecting other system operations
    **Scope**: CPU, memory, disk, network resource allocation
    
    ### SC-4: Network Security Safety
    **Constraint**: Container network access must be controlled and monitored
    **Rationale**: Prevent unauthorized network access or data exfiltration
    **Scope**: Port mappings, network policies, external connectivity
    
    ### SC-5: Configuration Consistency Safety
    **Constraint**: Container configurations must remain consistent with system policies
    **Rationale**: Prevent configuration drift leading to security or operational issues
    **Scope**: Environment variables, volume mounts, security policies
    
    ### SC-6: Development Workflow Safety
    **Constraint**: Container operations must not disrupt development productivity
    **Rationale**: Maintain developer efficiency while ensuring safety
    **Scope**: Build processes, testing workflows, debugging capabilities
    
    ✅ Safety Constraints: 6 constraints defined
    🎯 All container operations must maintain these constraints
    """
  end

  @doc """
  Models the control structure for container operations.
  
  ## Agent Notes
  Control structure identifies all system components and their control actions.
  Understanding control relationships is essential for UCA identification.
  """
  def model_control_structure do
    IO.puts """
    🏗️ STEP 2: CONTROL STRUCTURE MODELING  
    =====================================
    
    ## Container Operations Control Structure
    
    ### Controllers and Control Actions
    
    #### C1: Developer (Human Controller)
    **Control Actions**:
    • CA1-1: Issue container build commands
    • CA1-2: Execute development tasks in containers
    • CA1-3: Configure container environments
    • CA1-4: Monitor container performance
    
    **Feedback**:
    • FB1-1: Container build status and logs
    • FB1-2: Application performance metrics
    • FB1-3: Error messages and diagnostics
    • FB1-4: Resource usage information
    
    #### C2: Container Compliance System (Automated Controller)
    **Control Actions**:
    • CA2-1: Enforce container-only execution policy
    • CA2-2: Validate container environment requirements
    • CA2-3: Auto-correct host execution violations
    • CA2-4: Monitor compliance with safety constraints
    
    **Feedback**:
    • FB2-1: Compliance violation detection
    • FB2-2: Auto-correction success/failure status
    • FB2-3: Safety constraint monitoring results
    • FB2-4: System performance impact metrics
    
    #### C3: Podman Runtime (System Controller)
    **Control Actions**:
    • CA3-1: Create and start containers
    • CA3-2: Manage container lifecycle
    • CA3-3: Enforce resource limits
    • CA3-4: Provide container isolation
    
    **Feedback**:
    • FB3-1: Container status and health
    • FB3-2: Resource consumption metrics
    • FB3-3: Security and isolation status
    • FB3-4: Network connectivity status
    
    #### C4: NixOS Build System (Configuration Controller)
    **Control Actions**:
    • CA4-1: Build container images
    • CA4-2: Manage package dependencies
    • CA4-3: Configure container environments
    • CA4-4: Validate build reproducibility
    
    **Feedback**:
    • FB4-1: Build success/failure status
    • FB4-2: Dependency resolution results
    • FB4-3: Configuration validation results
    • FB4-4: Reproducibility verification status
    
    #### C5: PHICS Hot-Reloading System (Development Controller)
    **Control Actions**:
    • CA5-1: Monitor file system changes
    • CA5-2: Trigger automatic recompilation
    • CA5-3: Sync changes between host and container
    • CA5-4: Manage development server lifecycle
    
    **Feedback**:
    • FB5-1: File change detection events
    • FB5-2: Recompilation success/failure status
    • FB5-3: Sync operation status
    • FB5-4: Development server health status
    
    ### Control Relationships
    
    **Hierarchical Control**: Developer → Container Compliance → Podman Runtime
    **Peer Control**: Container Compliance ↔ PHICS System
    **Support Control**: NixOS Build System → All Controllers
    
    ✅ Control Structure: 5 controllers, 20 control actions identified
    🎯 Ready for Unsafe Control Action analysis
    """
  end

  @doc """
  Systematically identifies Unsafe Control Actions (UCAs).
  
  ## Agent Notes
  UCAs are control actions that, in particular contexts, can lead to safety
  constraint violations. Systematic identification prevents safety incidents.
  """
  def identify_unsafe_control_actions do
    IO.puts """
    ⚠️ STEP 3: UNSAFE CONTROL ACTION IDENTIFICATION
    ==============================================
    
    ## Systematic UCA Analysis Using STAMP Guide Words
    
    ### UCA Analysis for Control Action CA1-1: Issue container build commands
    
    #### UCA1-1-NOT-PROVIDED: Developer does not issue build command when needed
    **Context**: Application requires updated container after code changes
    **Hazard**: SC-6 violation - Development workflow disrupted by stale containers
    **Scenario**: Developer continues using outdated container with missing dependencies
    
    #### UCA1-1-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY: Developer issues build command with wrong parameters
    **Context**: Build command specifies incorrect image tags or build contexts
    **Hazard**: SC-5 violation - Configuration inconsistency causes runtime failures
    **Scenario**: Wrong base image leads to missing system dependencies
    
    #### UCA1-1-WRONG-TIME: Developer issues build command at inappropriate time
    **Context**: Build triggered during active development session or system maintenance
    **Hazard**: SC-6 violation - Workflow interruption or resource contention
    **Scenario**: Build interrupts debugging session or conflicts with system updates
    
    #### UCA1-1-STOPPED-TOO-SOON: Developer terminates build command prematurely
    **Context**: Long-running build process with complex dependency resolution
    **Hazard**: SC-2 violation - Incomplete build artifacts cause data integrity issues
    **Scenario**: Impatient termination leaves container in inconsistent state
    
    ### UCA Analysis for Control Action CA2-1: Enforce container-only execution
    
    #### UCA2-1-NOT-PROVIDED: Compliance system does not enforce container policy
    **Context**: Host execution attempt for development tasks
    **Hazard**: SC-1, SC-4 violations - Security and isolation compromised
    **Scenario**: Host execution bypasses container security controls
    
    #### UCA2-1-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY: Compliance system allows incorrect container usage
    **Context**: Wrong container image or configuration used for enforcement
    **Hazard**: SC-5 violation - Configuration drift from policy requirements
    **Scenario**: Development container used for production-like operations
    
    ### UCA Analysis for Control Action CA3-1: Create and start containers
    
    #### UCA3-1-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY: Podman creates container with incorrect configuration
    **Context**: Container creation with excessive privileges or wrong network settings
    **Hazard**: SC-1, SC-4 violations - Security isolation and network controls bypassed
    **Scenario**: Container started with --privileged flag or unrestricted network access
    
    #### UCA3-1-WRONG-TIME: Podman creates container when resources unavailable
    **Context**: System under resource pressure or during maintenance windows
    **Hazard**: SC-3 violation - Resource exhaustion affects system availability
    **Scenario**: Container creation during low-memory conditions causes system instability
    
    ### UCA Analysis for Control Action CA4-1: Build container images
    
    #### UCA4-1-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY: NixOS builds image with security vulnerabilities
    **Context**: Build process includes outdated packages or insecure configurations
    **Hazard**: SC-1 violation - Container security compromised from build time
    **Scenario**: Base image includes vulnerable packages or exposed services
    
    #### UCA4-1-STOPPED-TOO-SOON: NixOS build terminates before completion
    **Context**: Build process interrupted during critical package installation
    **Hazard**: SC-2 violation - Incomplete image leads to runtime failures
    **Scenario**: Network interruption during package download leaves image corrupted
    
    ### UCA Analysis for Control Action CA5-2: Trigger automatic recompilation
    
    #### UCA5-2-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY: PHICS triggers recompilation with wrong parameters
    **Context**: Recompilation with incorrect environment or missing dependencies
    **Hazard**: SC-6 violation - Development workflow disrupted by failed builds
    **Scenario**: Hot-reload triggers compilation with production settings in development
    
    #### UCA5-2-WRONG-TIME: PHICS triggers recompilation during critical operations
    **Context**: Recompilation during active debugging or testing sessions
    **Hazard**: SC-6 violation - Workflow interruption disrupts development process
    **Scenario**: File save during debugging triggers reload that breaks debug session
    
    ✅ UCA Analysis: 10 systematic UCAs identified across 5 control actions
    🎯 Causal scenario analysis required for prevention strategies
    """
  end

  @doc """
  Analyzes causal scenarios for identified UCAs.
  
  ## Agent Notes
  Causal analysis examines how UCAs can occur, focusing on:
  - Controller flaws (algorithms, process models)
  - Actuator failures
  - Sensor failures  
  - Communication issues
  """
  def analyze_causal_scenarios do
    IO.puts """
    🔍 STEP 4: CAUSAL SCENARIO ANALYSIS
    ==================================
    
    ## Systematic Causal Analysis for Critical UCAs
    
    ### Causal Analysis: UCA2-1-NOT-PROVIDED
    **UCA**: Compliance system does not enforce container policy when needed
    
    #### Controller Flaws (Container Compliance System)
    **Process Model Flaws**:
    • PM-1: Incorrect belief that execution is already in container
    • PM-2: Failure to detect host execution environment
    • PM-3: Outdated process model of system configuration
    
    **Algorithm Flaws**:
    • ALG-1: Detection algorithm fails on edge cases
    • ALG-2: Enforcement logic has conditional gaps
    • ALG-3: Error handling suppresses enforcement actions
    
    #### Communication Failures
    **Command Interface Issues**:
    • COM-1: Mix task bypasses compliance checking
    • COM-2: Script execution avoids compliance integration
    • COM-3: Developer uses alternative execution paths
    
    **Feedback Loop Failures**:
    • FB-1: Environment detection sensors provide false positives
    • FB-2: Compliance status reporting delayed or corrupted
    • FB-3: Violation alerts not received by monitoring systems
    
    ### Causal Analysis: UCA3-1-PROVIDED-INCORRECTLY  
    **UCA**: Podman creates container with incorrect security configuration
    
    #### Controller Flaws (Podman Runtime)
    **Configuration Processing**:
    • CONF-1: Security options parsing allows dangerous combinations
    • CONF-2: Default settings prioritize convenience over security
    • CONF-3: Command-line argument validation insufficient
    
    **Resource Management**:
    • RES-1: Resource limit enforcement uses incorrect thresholds
    • RES-2: Network isolation configuration allows unintended access
    • RES-3: Volume mount security context not properly applied
    
    #### External Dependencies
    **NixOS Integration Issues**:
    • NIX-1: Container image includes excessive privileges
    • NIX-2: Package selection includes unnecessary attack surface
    • NIX-3: Build-time security configurations overridden at runtime
    
    ### Causal Analysis: UCA5-2-WRONG-TIME
    **UCA**: PHICS triggers recompilation during critical development operations
    
    #### Controller Flaws (PHICS System)
    **Event Detection Logic**:
    • EVENT-1: File system monitoring too aggressive or indiscriminate
    • EVENT-2: Critical operation detection incomplete or inaccurate
    • EVENT-3: Timing coordination with other systems insufficient
    
    **State Management**:
    • STATE-1: Development session state tracking inadequate
    • STATE-2: Multi-user operation coordination missing
    • STATE-3: Resource contention detection and avoidance lacking
    
    #### Communication and Coordination
    **Inter-System Communication**:
    • COORD-1: PHICS lacks awareness of debugger state
    • COORD-2: Testing framework coordination insufficient
    • COORD-3: Build system status communication delayed
    
    ✅ Causal Analysis: 21 causal factors identified across 3 critical UCAs
    🎯 Safety requirements generation based on causal understanding
    """
  end

  @doc """
  Generates comprehensive safety requirements based on STPA analysis.
  
  ## Agent Notes
  Safety requirements directly address identified UCAs and their causal factors.
  Requirements are designed to prevent UCAs through systematic controls.
  """
  def generate_safety_requirements do
    IO.puts """
    📋 STEP 5: SAFETY REQUIREMENTS GENERATION
    ========================================
    
    ## Safety Requirements Based on STPA Analysis
    
    ### Category 1: Container Detection and Enforcement
    
    #### SR-1.1: Environment Detection Reliability
    **Requirement**: Container detection must use multiple independent methods
    **Rationale**: Prevents PM-1, PM-2 process model flaws
    **Implementation**: Environment variables + filesystem + process analysis + networking
    **Test**: Verify detection accuracy >99.9% across all environments
    
    #### SR-1.2: Enforcement Action Completeness  
    **Requirement**: All development commands must trigger compliance checking
    **Rationale**: Prevents COM-1, COM-2 communication bypass issues
    **Implementation**: Integration at Mix task level and script execution level
    **Test**: Verify no execution path bypasses compliance enforcement
    
    #### SR-1.3: Violation Response Immediacy
    **Requirement**: Compliance violations must trigger immediate corrective action
    **Rationale**: Prevents delayed or suppressed enforcement (ALG-3)
    **Implementation**: Synchronous violation handling with automatic correction
    **Test**: Verify <1 second response time for violation detection and correction
    
    ### Category 2: Container Security Configuration
    
    #### SR-2.1: Minimal Privilege Enforcement
    **Requirement**: Containers must operate with minimal required privileges
    **Rationale**: Prevents CONF-1, CONF-2 security configuration issues
    **Implementation**: Mandatory security option validation and defaults
    **Test**: Verify no container starts with unnecessary privileges
    
    #### SR-2.2: Network Isolation Validation
    **Requirement**: Container network access must be explicitly configured and validated
    **Rationale**: Prevents RES-2 network isolation configuration issues
    **Implementation**: Network policy validation before container start
    **Test**: Verify network access matches intended configuration exactly
    
    #### SR-2.3: Volume Mount Security
    **Requirement**: Volume mounts must use appropriate security contexts
    **Rationale**: Prevents RES-3 volume mount security issues
    **Implementation**: Automatic SELinux context application (:z flags)  
    **Test**: Verify all volume mounts have correct security contexts
    
    ### Category 3: Build System Safety
    
    #### SR-3.1: Image Security Validation
    **Requirement**: Container images must pass security validation before use
    **Rationale**: Prevents NIX-1, NIX-2 excessive privileges and attack surface
    **Implementation**: Automated security scanning integrated into build process
    **Test**: Verify all images pass security validation with A+ rating
    
    #### SR-3.2: Build Completeness Verification
    **Requirement**: Container builds must complete all phases or fail safely
    **Rationale**: Prevents build interruption causing incomplete images
    **Implementation**: Atomic build process with rollback on incomplete builds
    **Test**: Verify build interruption never produces usable incomplete images
    
    ### Category 4: Development Workflow Safety
    
    #### SR-4.1: Operation Context Awareness
    **Requirement**: PHICS must detect and respect critical development operations
    **Rationale**: Prevents EVENT-1, EVENT-2 inappropriate timing issues
    **Implementation**: Integration with debuggers, test runners, and build systems
    **Test**: Verify hot-reload respects debugging and testing sessions
    
    #### SR-4.2: Resource Contention Prevention
    **Requirement**: Container operations must avoid resource conflicts
    **Rationale**: Prevents STATE-3 resource contention issues
    **Implementation**: Resource monitoring and operation scheduling
    **Test**: Verify container operations don't cause resource exhaustion
    
    #### SR-4.3: Multi-User Coordination
    **Requirement**: Container system must coordinate across multiple development sessions
    **Rationale**: Prevents STATE-2 multi-user operation coordination issues
    **Implementation**: Session management and resource locking
    **Test**: Verify multiple developers can work simultaneously without conflicts
    
    ### Category 5: Monitoring and Feedback
    
    #### SR-5.1: Real-Time Status Monitoring
    **Requirement**: All container operations must provide real-time status feedback
    **Rationale**: Prevents FB-1, FB-2 feedback loop failures
    **Implementation**: Comprehensive logging and metrics collection
    **Test**: Verify status updates available within 100ms of state changes
    
    #### SR-5.2: Alert System Reliability
    **Requirement**: Safety constraint violations must trigger reliable alerts
    **Rationale**: Prevents FB-3 alert delivery failures
    **Implementation**: Multiple alert channels with delivery confirmation
    **Test**: Verify 100% alert delivery for all safety constraint violations
    
    ✅ Safety Requirements: 11 requirements generated addressing all identified UCAs
    🎯 Implementation integration with existing safety systems required
    """
  end

  @doc """
  Integrates STPA analysis results with existing systems.
  
  ## Agent Notes
  Integration ensures STPA findings are systematically implemented
  in existing container compliance and safety systems.
  """
